      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p><i>tert</i>-Butyl esters [RCO<sub>2</sub>C(CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>] are converted into carboxylic acids (RCO<sub>2</sub>H) by reaction with trifluoroacetic acid, a reaction useful in protein synthesis <b>(Section 26.7)</b>. Assign <i>E,Z</i> designation to the double bonds of both reactant and product in the following scheme, and explain why there is an apparent change in double-bond stereochemistry:</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaEVTIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--75e88214e1d339b19a2eb29b019299a19dcaf789/OChem_07_EC_033.jpg\" alt=\"The figure shows tertiary-butyl ester reacts with trifluoroacetic acid to form a carboxylic acid and an alkene.\">",
